==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*bōkjōn'', from ''*bōkō'', from Indo-European ''*bhagos''.  Cognate with Middle Low German [[boke|bōke]]; and (''from the Germanic root'') with Old Saxon [[boka|bōka]] (Dutch [[beuk]]), Old High German [[buohha]] (German [[Buche]]), Old Norse [[bók]] (Swedish [[bok]]).  The Indo-European root is also the source of Greek [[φηγός]] ‘oak’, Latin [[fagus]] ‘beech’, Russian [[бузина]] ‘elder-tree’.

